A word to the wise - as you write your bio for linkedin, do not write your rough drafts in the linkedin box.  Why? Because chrome can crash, linkedin can be weird, and ultimately your hard work can disappear.  I speak from experience  :disappointed:

As long as I can remember, I've loved to be in front of people. Whether I was emoting scenes as an actor or explaining difficult concepts as a teacher, seeing someone "get it" made my day. After college, I translated that passion into a career by becoming a technical trainer and applications engineer. Apparently I was not the only one aware of my passion. I was given the opportunity to manage the training and technical program management for my department and then the entire company.

At Evans Analytical Group, I've had the opportunity to manage global training for the entire company by building its first corporate university from the ground up. This opportunity has been in parallel with my  role of leading the technical program management team. The desire to learn the connection between data and the bottom line made me interested in data science. Which is why I am a data scientist today.

I am passionate about turning data into meaningful stories. Currently, I'm working on machine learning models and data engineering. . During my Masters in Data science at GalvanizeU, I have built statistical data analysis project. 

- Interests: Machine Learning, Deep Learning, Natural Language Processing, Learning and Development, Program Mgt
- Languages: Python, C, C++
- Frameworks and Tools: Apache Spark Ecosystem (Streaming/ SQL/ MLlib/ GraphX), Hadoop( HDFS, YARN, MapReduce)

I am passionate about turning data into meaningful stories. Currently, I'm developing machine learning models for anomaly detection project. This project aims to improve fraud detection for mobile games played by millions. During my Masters in Data science at GalvanizeU, I worked with Skymind, Databricks and Wikipedia on industry data science projects. Prior to joining the GalvanizeU MS Data Science program, I held positions as a Microsoft Student Partner, and Wikipedia campus ambassador. I also co-founded Synergiclinks in London, where I led a team of five engineers in designing civic apps and grew my skills in data management, engineering, and marketing.

- Interests: Deep Learning, Natural Language Processing, Data Engineering and Design
- Languages: Python, Java; Beginner: Scala, Go
- Frameworks and Tools: Apache Spark Ecosystem (Streaming/ SQL/ MLlib/ GraphX), Hadoop( HDFS, YARN, MapReduce)

I love making connections. I am passionate about discovering nonintuitive patterns with data, and I want to enable people to make informed, data-driven decisions. This is why I am a data scientist. 

I am a Data Scientist with a formal education in applied mathematics and 3 years of programming experience. I have professional experience as an actuarial analyst and as a programmer in the health insurance and financial industries, respectively. I’ve acquired knowledge in machine learning applications, natural language processing, and data engineering. I am familiar with supervised regression and classification techniques, as well as unsupervised techniques such as clustering and Non negative factorization. In my latest project, I used the presidential debate text to train a Naive Bayes classifier that can classify statements to a specific candidate.

Before I entered the field of data science, I was a programmer for a fortune 500 Financial Services company. Hired on with almost zero programming knowledge, within two years I became a subject matter expert on a data pipeline application. This application transformed VSAM (mainframe) datasets to a relational database that then integrated with a BI reporting tool. As a SME for this application, I was not only responsible for developing custom implementations, but I was also responsible for developing project outlines, estimates, timelines, and planning documents for full software deployment.

My programming language of choice is Python, where I frequently use numpy, pandas, scikit-learn, nltk, and matplotlib. In addition, I am also proficient in SQL, Linux, bash, COBOL, and have experience with Apache Spark, Hadoop, and AWS.

I focus on building great products with data.
Been fortunate to build some incredible teams in the consumer and enterprise space
Had to fight lots of bad guys in the cyber arena
Had some good luck in Academia working on chaos theory
Worked in two Administrations on domestic & national security issues.

Here's a bit more detail:
Most recently DJ was appointed by President Obama to be the first U.S. Chief Data Scientist where his efforts led to the establishment of nearly 40 Chief Data Officer roles across the Federal government. He also established new health care programs including the Precision Medicine Initiative and the Cancer Moonshot, new criminal justice reforms including the Data-Driven Justice and Police Data Initiatives that cover more than 94 million Americans, as well as leading the national data efforts. He also has been active in national security and for his efforts was awarded by Secretary Carter the Dept. of Defense Medal for Distinguished Public Service which the highest honor the department bestows on a civilian. 

In industry, he led the product teams at RelateIQ which was acquired by Salesforce, was founding board member for Crisis Text Line which works to use new technologies to provide on demand mental and crisis support, and was a member of the venture firm Greylock Partners. He has also was Chief Scientist, Chief Security Officer and Head of Analytics and Data Product Teams at the LinkedIn Corporation where he co-coined the term Data Scientist. He has also held a number of roles at Skype, PayPal, and eBay. 

As a member of the faculty at the University of Maryland, his research focused on nonlinear dynamics and chaos theory and he helped start a major research initiative on numerical weather prediction. As an AAAS Science & Technology Policy Fellow for the Department of Defense, Dr. Patil directed new efforts to leverage social network analysis and the melding of computational and social sciences to anticipate emerging threats to the US

Austin, Texas - Galvanize TRIP SUMMARY:

Hello All:
Here are photos of Galvanize Austin from my trip last week.   In short,  you have all indicated an interest in this visit, here is a summary of what I’ve learned

1)	It is possible to get a job placement in Austin (or the State of Texas through the contacts made by the Austin location) by the nature Galvanize’s national presence.   To do so however, we must strictly go through MaryAnn and not through the local Office of interest.
2)	Galvanize jobs board & job placement is centered on a specific site where we post our profiles, a site that Galvanize curates – which we will find out from MaryAnn at some point in the future.
3)	Our idea that we discussed prior to my trip – where we can get a company outside of SF, to consider gU5 students for an internship or capstone -- is currently not a reality for the entire Galvanize national network at this time.  This was made clear during my Austin visit.  
4)	However, if we are all still interested in such a capstone /internship for ourselves or most likely as an option for future cohorts we may want to mention in our upcoming career service meetings with MaryAnn.

I had a great and highly productive trip, and am happy to share what I learned with you. 
	Rafa

attachments.title: Twitch And Mixpanel Fireside Chat
attachments.text: Data scientists and machine learning engineers are both creative, technical and interdisciplinary thinkers, and some of the rarest experts across startups and enterprise companies. Their contributions can impact departments across product, marketing, design, operations, and beyond. But in order for innovative businesses to grow and build excellent products, companies must understand the different applications and values behind each discipline. For this March’s Super Office Hours event, Twitch and Mixpanel join forces in a Fireside Chat to discuss why data science and machine learning are two of the most important practices to invest in for company growth. Danny Hernandez, Data Scientist at Twitch, and Jenny Finkel, Head of Machine Learning at Mixpanel, examine how companies use these superpowers to leverage data in more sophisticated ways and build products that win. In this conversation, moderated by Amelia Salyers, Editor of Mixpanel's The Signal, Danny and Jenny will break down the complex concepts of data science and machine learning to help us understand exactly why these two fields will build empires in the new era of technology.
